data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Core Problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core+. The entire pattern must be replaced with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException — matches original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>Async overload — preferred in modern code.</summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage (before → after)

```csharp
// ── BEFORE (.NET Framework) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── AFTER (.NET 8) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Synchronous — work must check the token
var data = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// Async — preferred
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | `CancellationToken` is *cooperative* — if `work` ignores the token, it keeps running after timeout. There is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Abort()`. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | After timeout, `Task.Run` may still be executing. If the delegate holds resources (DB connections, file handles), it leaks until it finishes or checks the token. |
| **Signature change is breaking** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>` — all callers must be updated. Provide a legacy shim if needed (see below). |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removal** | Simply delete it — `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception, no "reset" concept. |
| **`task.Result` vs `await`** | `.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException` (matching the original). `await` unwraps to the inner exception — different behavior. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** | The original code created a foreground `Thread`; `Task.Run` uses pool threads. If `work` sets thread-static or `ThreadLocal<T>` state, it won't behave the same. |

### Legacy Shim (for unmodifiable callers)

```csharp
// Wraps a token-unaware delegate. The work CANNOT be stopped early —
// it runs to completion even after timeout.
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    return ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => work(), timeout);
}
```

> ⚠️ This silently hides the fact that the work keeps running — use it only as a transitional bridge, not permanently.

### Hardened variant for non-cooperative work

If you truly cannot modify the work delegate (e.g., third-party code), and you need the closest thing to the old `Abort()` behavior:

```csharp
// Last resort: runs work on a dedicated thread and abandons it on timeout.
// The thread is NOT terminated — it runs until it finishes or the process exits.
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    T result = default!;
    Exception? error = null;

    var thread = new Thread(() =>
    {
        try { result = work(); }
        catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
    })
    { IsBackground = true }; // won't block process exit

    thread.Start();

    if (!thread.Join(timeout))
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout (thread abandoned)");

    if (error != null)
        throw new AggregateException(error);

    return result;
}
```

**Bottom line:** Push `CancellationToken` through to the actual I/O wherever possible — it's the only way to get real cancellation in .NET 8.
